        "timestamp": 1676329065
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In fact I think I was talking to Ohad about this at POPL and I think he called such a theory an idempotent theory</p>",
        "id": 327679074,
        "sender_full_name": "Max New",
        "timestamp": 1676338978
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Theories satisfying this condition (which look to be called relevant in Kammar–Plotkin's paper) were called hyperaffine by Johnstone in <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002186939090230L\">Collapsed toposes and cartesian closed varieties</a>.</p>",
        "id": 327689123,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1676347865
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think \"idempotent theory\" is a misleading term, because usually \"P theories\" correspond to \"P monads\" under the monad–theory correspondence for some property P, and that's not true here.</p>",
        "id": 327689144,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1676347902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When monads are used to model collection types in union presentation, idempotency is one of the four axes along which the collection can vary in the so-called \"Boom Hierarchy\".  For example, the set monad is idempotent because set union is but the list monad is not because list append is not.  The others are associativity, commutativity, and existence of a unit.  Here's a paper: <a href=\"https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/document?repid=rep1&amp;type=pdf&amp;doi=dd3ed1c7d523781513f01d25e1be472de4279d72\">https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/document?repid=rep1&amp;type=pdf&amp;doi=dd3ed1c7d523781513f01d25e1be472de4279d72</a> and blog post <a href=\"https://blog.acolyer.org/2014/11/06/the-boom-hierarchy/\">https://blog.acolyer.org/2014/11/06/the-boom-hierarchy/</a></p>",
        "id": 327707075,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Wisnesky",
        "timestamp": 1676359781
    }
]